nodes.title: (Input Mode) depending on the image type:

widgets_values:
{(Input Mode) Rescale Input Image to}
Controls the rescaling behaviour for the loaded ControNet Image.

0 = OFF - Use the original dimensions of the loaded image
1 = to shorter - Scale the loaded image so that its width or height (whichever is shorter) matches the corresponding setting
2 = to width - Scale the loaded image so that its width matches the width setting
3 = to height - Scale the loaded image so that its height matches the height setting

In every rescaling option, the image aspect ratio remains the same as in the original image

Rescaling will require you to manually calculate the width or height (depending on the setting) for setting subject areas.

If you have the 'show-text' custom node by pythongosssss you can find it calculated automatically next to the setting (mind that it only updates when running the workflow so queue prompt => cancel once it updates => set subject areas => queue again).
Link: https://github.com/pythongosssss/ComfyUI-Custom-Scripts/tree/main/show-text

The values are floored so that 1.5 becomes 1 etc

nodes.title: About
widgets_values:
This workflow utilises the ControlNet OpenPose model and area composition to achieve character interaction with separate prompts for each character at high consistency.

#############################################################################
 -------------------------------WORKFLOW MODES------------------------------
#############################################################################
This workflow features 2 modes, you can select the mode by changing the values of the black node near the bottom of the [Global Settings & Loaders] group. There are:

1) Input Mode: 
  The image you provide will be applied to the generation for guidance
The dimensions of the image will be set according to the setting chosen in the {(Input Mode) Rescale to} node at the bottom of [Global Settings & Loaders]
  You can either input an OpenPose image or an unprocessed image from which a pose will be extracted. Depending on which it is, set the correct value in the switch below {Load Image for ControlNet} in [Global Settings & Loaders]

2) Generate Mode:
The workflow will first generate an image in [Area & Pose]
 - This will use dimensions specified in [Global Settings & Loaders]
 - This will only use the {Pose & Background} prompt (cyan)
 - This will use the checkpoint and VAE specified in [Area & Pose]
The resulting image will be passed through ControlNet OpenPose Preprocessor to extract the pose
 (The above is only to generate the pose image)
Afterwards, the proper image generation will begin using the usual settings from [Global Settings & Loaders] and prompt areas set in [Area & Pose]. The 
pose image generated in the previous step will be used for guidance.

Notes:
 - In Input Mode, an image will still be generated in [Area & Pose] but the resulting OpenPose image will not be used. This is a problem with ComfyUI and circumventing it would require an additional switch in an awkward spot which I opted not to make as things are complicated enough already. Generation time will be slightly prolonged because of this.
 - In Generate Mode a separate checkpoint is used as different checkpoints have a varied knowledge of poses, letting you use the pose knowledge from one checkpoint and then for the proper generation switch to another one that has a more preferable art style for instance
 - In Generate Mode it may be preferable to use a realistic model as the OpenPose preprocessor has an easier time detecting poses in realistic characters. 2.5D anime models should work well too.
 - In Generate Mode, you can enable/disable the detection of body, hands and facial features in the {Openpose Preprocessor} node on the right of [Area & Pose]
 - Don't get dissuaded by Openpose Preprocessor finding only one character or interpreting both characters' faces as one (this can happen when faces are close together and turned towards each other). Almost always both characters will be generated properly anyways.

#############################################################################
 -------------------------SUBJECT AREAS AND PREVIEW-------------------------
#############################################################################
 - Specify subject dimensions and locations in [Area & Pose]. The set areas will be visualized in the [Subject Visualization] image preview once image generation has reached a certain point. Some area overlap is desired, especially with close interactions
  - Subject 1 will be marked in blue
  - Subject 2 will be marked in green

 - In Input Mode, the overall initial image dimensions are overwritten by those of the provided image, but areas still have to be set manually
 - In Generate Mode, where the characters appear is not under control so it's best to keep the framing such that the characters occupy most of the space to ensure that conditioning areas are properly located
 - Ideally, the visualization would appear as soon as possible to give feedback o whether the areas are set correctly, but the features necessary to force this order in a generation are not yet implemented in ComfyUI

#############################################################################
 ----------------------------------PROMPTS----------------------------------
#############################################################################
 - The quality preset selected at the top of PROMPT will be added at the beginning of both subject prompts. The selector has a step of 0.5, but the value is rounded down, so 1.5 will choose the preset with the number 1 and so on
- The Pose & Background prompt has a separate quality prompt that is used in pose image generation in Generate Mode (because you can use a different checkpoint here). For the proper generation, the above-selected preset is used.

#############################################################################
 -----------------------------ITERATIVE UPSCALE-----------------------------
#############################################################################
Iterative upscale (from Impact Pack) in [2nd Pass] upscales the image in smaller increments and passes it through a sampler on each step, resulting in better quality and detail at the cost of speed.
 - {Upscale Factor} decides the final size increase
 - {Upscale steps} decide the number of steps in which upscaling is divided. If set to 1 it is identical to normal upscaling.

If set for example to: Upscale Factor = 2, Upscale Steps = 4, then it will do the following: upscale 1.25, sampler pass, upscale 1.5, sampler pass, upscale 1.75, sampler pass, upscale 2, sampler pass (upscale values are relative to original size)

#############################################################################
 ------------------------GENERATING A SINGLE SUBJECT------------------------
#############################################################################
Generating a single subject is not very efficient as you'll still have to either input an image in Input mode or generate a new one in Generate mode but it is possible

 - To do so, leave both subject prompts blank and use only the background prompt or use the background prompt for pose and perspective like usual and one of the subject prompts for the rest. The latter approach allows for a bit more control
 - In Generate mode it will allow you to create a pose with one checkpoint and the rest with another, so there is a slight versatility advantage over a normal generation. You'll also be able to save the pose by right-clicking the first preview image

#############################################################################
 -------------------ADJUSTING CONDITIONING VISUALISATION--------------------
#############################################################################
This section is mainly intended for those who struggle to see the subject areas in the [Conditioning Visualisation].

The colours and opacity of subject areas can be adjusted in {Subject 1 RGB}/{Subject 2 RGB} and {Area Opacity} nodes respectively. They can be found immediately to the right of the subject area settings in the [Area & Pose] group

#############################################################################
 --------------------------------OBSERVATIONS-------------------------------
#############################################################################
This section is dedicated to some of my (workflow's author's) observations about its functioning.

 1) When a character occupies a very non-rectangular area, for example, arms extending beyond in a hug, it becomes impossible to affect the entire character with our prompt without affecting others. Therefore in close interactions such as hugs, it may be a good idea to prompt the arms/hands and their garments in the other character's prompt box. The same applies to other body parts that cross subject areas like that.

 2) Despite cropping the ControlNet OpenPose image, there are surprisingly few problems springing from having essentially disjointed limbs coming in from out-of-frame into subject areas. Aside from #1 of course.

 3) The ControlNet OpenPose Preprocessor is *not great* at detecting faces that aren't turned directly towards the camera, particularly when it can't see both eyes. This is especially apparent with character interactions such as kissing when it will interpret both faces as one (it sees 2 ears, 2 eyes and 2 noses close to each other or one, the other being covered, so for it, it's a perfectly fine face despite the ears and eyes belonging to separate characters). Despite this, the generation has next to no noticeable trouble handling this. What happens is each subject's conditioning only gets a cropped part of the OpenPose image as guidance essentially cutting away the part of the face that doesn't belong to that subject leaving only one nose, eye and ear which means a sideways perspective thus fixing the entire problem. The only little quirk that remains is both characters' noses will always appear in the same spot in these situations.

#############################################################################
 -----------------------------------OTHER-----------------------------------
#############################################################################
 - Black nodes are switches that enable/disable certain functions and switch between certain options (eg. upscaling using latent upscale vs an upscale model)

 - The black VAE reroute near [Global Settings & Loaders] is connected to all relevant nodes besides those in [Area & Pose]
 - The black VAE reroute in [Area & Pose] is connected to all relevant nodes in [Area & Pose]

 - With 2 faces, face restoration will run twice, once for each face, prolonging generation time. Just a heads up.

- Grid Size for this workflow is 25
